TI  - Response of litter ants (Hymenoptera: Formicidae) to habitat heterogeneity and local resource availability in native and exotic forests
T2  - SOCIOBIOLOGY
AB  - This study tested the response of litter ant species to environmental heterogeneity and resource availability. Samples of 30 x 30 cm of litter were collected in three habitats (native forest, Eucalyptus sp. crop and Pinus sp. crop) and the ants were extracted using a Berlese funnel. We used litter weight and composition, tree species richness and abundance as surrogates of heterogeneity and resource availability. The influence of these variables on litter ant species richness and abundance in the habitats was tested by covariance analyses. A Chao 2 index was used to estimate ant species diversity in each habitat. None of the parameters significantly influenced litter ant species richness and abundance. Only litter ant abundance responded to habitat and was higher in the Eucalyptus crop. The absence of response of litter ants is probably due to the influence of other factors involved, such as local disturbances. Similarities in habitat complexity of the habitats could also have accounted for the absence of response observed, given that the understory of both Eucalyptus and Pinus crops is in an advanced stage of regeneration, implying that they could have recovered from anthropic impacts.
