AU  - Peixoto, OCMO
AU  - Carvalho, MD
AU  - de Sousa JR Jr
AU  - Monteiro, JM
TI  - Wound response of the bark of two semiarid medicinal tree species: implications for conservation
T2  - ENVIRONMENT DEVELOPMENT AND SUSTAINABILITY
AB  - Exploitation of plant parts in an unsustainable way can lead to the death of important species and thus a loss in biodiversity. The aim of this study was to evaluate the stem bark regeneration rate of two semiarid medicinal tree species, as well as relating to rainfall, diameter and height. Ten individuals of each species were selected in the study area, with no signs of predation. Bark extractions corresponding to 20 cm(2) and 30 cm(2) were carried out. The healing rate of Terminalia glabrescens Mart. was significantly higher than the other species studied. After six months, a greater regeneration process was observed for T. glabrescens Mart., with 60% of the area regenerated. For C. langsdorffii Desf., in the same period, the regenerated area was smaller, around 30%. The size of the damage to the stem bark of plants is important for their regeneration and that extractions must be made in the smallest size possible. The height and thickness of the individuals did not influence bark regeneration, but it is suggested that the bark be extracted from larger and thicker plants. Healing and resistance to infection after damage to the stem bark can be influenced by plant physiology, presence of exudates or even genetic characteristics related to the plant family or individuals. It is recommended to remove the bark from the stem in thin strips and wait at least two years before collecting them again. These actions will help the individual resist damage with greater resilience. Studies that make it possible to understand the stem bark regeneration strategies of species appreciated by human populations are important and can facilitate the implementation of adequate management and reduce existing extinction processes, as there is no information on the planting of these trees, the cost of human labor in collecting these stem barks or recording the quantity collected of this resource.
