TI  - Somatic embryogenesis and plant regeneration from zygotic embryos of the palm tree Euterpe precatoria Mart
T2  - PLANT CELL TISSUE AND ORGAN CULTURE
AB  - Euterpe precatoria Mart. (acai) it is a native palm of the Amazonian biome of environmental and socioeconomic importance. However, its exploitation has a predatory extractive character, its sexual propagation is slow and heterogeneous and the species does not till. Therefore, the development of efficient propagation methods is crucial to leverage their sustainable exploitation. Thus, this work aimed to develop a protocol of somatic embryogenesis of the species from mature zygotic embryos. Explants were inoculated in Murashige and Skoog (MS) or Eeuwens (Y3) media supplemented with 2,4-dichlorophenoxyacetic acid (2,4-D) or 4-amino-3,5,6-trichloropicolinic acid (Picloram) at five concentrations (0, 6.79, 13.57, 20.36, 27.15 mu M). After 90 days, they were transferred to a multiplication medium, with a low concentration of auxins, associated with 2-isopentenyladenine (2iP). Histodifferentiation and maturation of embryos was performed half strength Y3 medium or added 0.54 mu M 1-naphthaleneacetic acid and 12.3 mu M 2iP. It was found that the formation of embryogenic calluses and somatic embryos was influenced by culture medium, auxin type and concentration of regulators, especially the culture medium Y3 supplemented with 13.57 and 20.36 mu M Picloram. By means of morphoanatomic analyses, different types of embryogenic calluses were identified, somatic embryos with suspensor-like structures, indicating unicellular origin, as well as secondary embryogenesis. High rate of proliferation of embryogenic structures and complete germination of somatic embryos were found, with 92.3% survival after acclimatization. This unprecedented protocol will subsidize mass-scale propagation and the development of breeding and genetic conservation programs of the species.
   Key message This work details an unprecedented protocol of somatic embryogenesis from zygotic embryos of Euterpe precatoria, a palm tree native from the Amazon biome with great socioeconomic potential.
