TI  - The Catacumba Trail environmental project
T2  - SUSTAINABLE CITY: URBAN REGENERATION AND SUSTAINABILITY
CP  - 1st International Conference on Urban Regeneration and Sustainability (The Sustainable City 2000)
AB  - Located in the south zone of the city the Catacumba Trail is a joint project developed by the NPD (Design Research Nucleus of UniverCidade) and the Municipal Secretary of Environment.
   The trail starts at the Rodrigo the Freitas lagoon and leads up to the top of Sacopa hill where visitors enjoy a splendid view of Ipanema and Leblon, the Botanical Garden and the Tijuca Forest. Once an indigenous cemetery (catacomb) and later a slum, the area is now a Municipal Park by the "shores" of the densely populated Lagoon neighbourhood. From this park the trail goes up for 400 meters through the remains of the slum and what we believe are colonial ruins. Alongside the trail there are small flat areas where the NPD installed a signing system to introduce historical and environmental information. During its first year of operation the NPD monitors and the municipal guard received and conduced at the place more than 15000 visitors, many of them children from the local net of schools. Our monitors also developed games, brochures and slide shows to be used in loco and at the preparatory visits in the schools.
   Presently UniverCidade and the Municipal Secretary are preparing some workings at the place which include the second phase of the reforestation process (secondary and climax species) and the signing of an alternative descent route in order to create a circular trail design. In the city this trail was the first to be signed by an inter-disciplinary design team and consequently offers a model and functions as a laboratory to other environmental projects at other natural areas of the city like the Tijuca Forest Park.
